Middleware
Middleware are the special functions that run between or in the middle of request coming in or response going out of our API. Middleware is
defined inside the app.use() with a function that takes the request, response and next as the parameters. Where the next points to the
middleware below the ongoing middleware. The middleware without the next function is thus called the endpoint, and is determined by
app.METHOD() such as GET,PUT etc.
Fig. Middleware Execution process in EXpressJS
express.json() is built in express middleware function that understands when the request is being passed in as JSON based content-type
header option, it will do the parsing for us and set the req.body parameter.
Syntax: app.use(express.json());
When a client (like a frontend app or API client) sends an HTTP request with a Content-Type: application/json header and a JSON body:
This middleware parses that JSON into a JavaScript object and makes it available as req.body in your route handlers.
If you don’t use express.json(), then req.body will be undefined when trying to handle JSON input.
Model-View-Controller(MVC)
Modern Express Applications use the MVC pattern to organize and structure the code. Its the pattern that tells how our code should be
organized based on what they do. MVC makes the code understandable.
Fig. Model View Controller Layout
Controller - Controller is the code or the function that react to the incoming response and set the response accordingly.
Model - Model is our data, or the function used to access the database. It includes schemas, and databases handling ways, for making
efficient use of the data.
View - Views are how the data in model is presented back to user. Eg graphs, htmls. Views may also be the API and the JSON data we
send back through it.
-Biplav Paudel
RESTful APIs
RESTful APIs (Representational State Transfer APIs) are a set of conventions for building web services that allow different systems to
communicate over the internet. They are based on the principles of REST, which is an architectural style for designing networked
applications. Here are some key characteristics of RESTful APIs:
-Stateless: Each request from a client to a server must contain all the information needed to understand and process the
request. This means that the server does not need to remember previous requests.
-Resource-Based: RESTful APIs are centered around resources, which are identified by URLs. Each resource can be manipulated using
standard HTTP methods. Endpoints point to the resource or the collection of data.
-HTTP Methods: RESTful APIs typically use standard HTTP methods to perform operations on resources:
GET: Retrieve data from the server.
POST: Create a new resource on the server.
PUT: Update an existing resource on the server.
DELETE: Remove a resource from the server.
Representation: Resources can have multiple representations, such as JSON, XML, or HTML. Clients interact with resources through these
representations.
Uniform Interface: RESTful APIs have a uniform interface that simplifies and decouples the architecture, allowing different clients to
interact with the server in a consistent manner.
Cacheable: Responses from the server can be marked as cacheable or non-cacheable, allowing clients to cache responses to improve
performance.
RESTful APIs are widely used in web development due to their simplicity, scalability, and ease of integration with various platforms and
technologies. They are commonly used in web applications, mobile applications, and microservices architectures .

Serving static files with express.static middleware
Syntax:
app.use('/files[optional]',express.static(path.join(__dirname,"public")));
In Express.js, the .static middleware is used to serve static files like HTML, CSS, JavaScript, images, fonts, etc. It is part of the core
express module and is commonly used to serve assets from a folder, such as a public directory. It can be accesses via http://url:port/site-
/filename
The benefit of doing this is that we can also access the other related static files like CSS linked to or images displayed by the served html.
We may also use content delivery network(CDN) like Akamai or Amazon Cloudfront to store the static files via this method for scalability.
Note: After this all the client side code should have the path relative to the static folder ie:public folder in this case.
Steps to use templating engine in express
1. Install the template engine package npm i <template_package_name>
2. Set the view engine to EJS
app.set('view engine', 'ejs');
3. Set the views directory (optional if using default "views")
app.set('views', path.join(__dirname, 'views'));
4. Define a route
app.get('/', (req, res) => {
res.render('index', { title: 'My EJS Page', message: 'Hello from EJS!' });
The /files is optional that means if we add that the static files will only be accessed by routes
like /files/images/logo.jpg but not by root i.e. '/' route.
Using Layouts in the Handlebars(HBS) templates
Create a layout.hbs inside the views folder with default part eg.navbar {{{body}}} for the dynamic part.
The layout may also contain the dynamic variables eg. {{title}}.
Create other hbs files that we want to serve dynamically eg.profile.hbs,settings.hbs containing only the specific part
not contained by layout.
Use the default way to render in the server file.
res.render('profile.hbs',{[object containg hbs variables eg. title: 'My site']})
